Undid revision 850819257 by [[Special:Contributions/Slightlymad|Slightlymad]] ([[User talk:Slightlymad|talk]]) Somebody teach this guy about genres. Martial arts and action isn't the exactly same thing. He feels since director said it's not martial arts, it's not action film. Nothing on earth can change the fact that it's an action film first and foremost. Martial arts is action, but action isn't necessarily martial arts.

Added the source to real genre: action. The thing is, what directors normally describe is an opinion. And opinions are mostly subjective and not always accurate on facts. Now that it's done, I don't want any pointless report threats in the name of vandalism on my talk page any more. Because I've only fixed the wrong thing, and not vandalised anything.

Many a times even the directors don't have an idea about what they're saying. The Raid 2 is an out and out action movie, and crime is merely an element to bridge up the action. Don't make more such edits because it fits accurately in the action genre. If you're so interested in making edits, make it to the page of Dunkirk, which is not believed to be a war film by its director but still is mentioned as one.

Yes, not martial arts. But not a full crime film either. It's an action movie with crime elements. Just saying crime would mean it's not necessarily action film. Both Raid movies are known for their action, nor story.
